docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The entire federal appeals court in Washington said on Friday that it would take up two cases that raised the question of whether and when Congress may sue to resolve a dispute with the president, setting up a double-barreled test for establishing when the judicial branch can resolve disputes over separation of powers.

headline.main: Full Appeals Court to Decide Whether Congress Can Sue Executive Branch
headline.print_headline: Full Appeals Court to Decide if Congress Can Sue Executive Branch

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump declared a national emergency on Friday over the coronavirus pandemic and announced steps he said would speed the availability of testing, and early Saturday, the House passed a bill reflecting a deal with his administration to provide billions of dollars to help sick workers and to prop up a slumping economy.

headline.main: House Passes Coronavirus Relief After Democrats Strike Deal With White House
headline.print_headline: U.S. Emergency Declared; Aid Deal Is Reached

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump tested negative for the coronavirus, the White House physician said on Saturday, a week after having contact with multiple people who days later tested positive for the virus.

headline.main: Trump Tests Negative for Coronavirus, His Doctor Says

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The global spread of the coronavirus is reigniting efforts by the Trump administration to encourage more American manufacturing of pharmaceuticals and reduce dependence on China for the drugs and medical products that fuel the federal health care system.

headline.main: Coronavirus Spurs U.S. Efforts to End China’s Chokehold on Drugs
headline.print_headline: Virus Spurs U.S. Efforts to End China’s Chokehold on Drugs

docs.abstract: The rule, struck down by a bipartisan majority, sought to rewrite Obama-era debt relief measures, which allow students misled by schools to request that their loan debts be forgiven.
docs.snippet: The rule, struck down by a bipartisan majority, sought to rewrite Obama-era debt relief measures, which allow students misled by schools to request that their loan debts be forgiven.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In a bipartisan rebuke, the Senate voted on Wednesday to overturn a major Trump administration rule that would sharply limit debt relief for students misled by schools that lured them in with false claims about their graduates’ career and earning prospects.

headline.main: Senate Rejects DeVos Rule Restricting Debt Relief for Bilked Students
headline.print_headline: Senate Rejects DeVos Rule Limiting Debt Relief for Defrauded Students

byline.original: By Erica L. Green and Stacy Cowley

docs.abstract: Democrats planned a Thursday vote on an aid package as the Treasury secretary said he hoped for a deal on a first phase of economic stimulus within 48 hours.
docs.snippet: Democrats planned a Thursday vote on an aid package as the Treasury secretary said he hoped for a deal on a first phase of economic stimulus within 48 hours.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The White House and Democrats rushed on Wednesday to reach agreement on emergency legislation to provide a first tranche of economic assistance to help Americans cope with the fast-moving coronavirus pandemic, with the hope of sending it to President Trump for his signature by the end of the week.

headline.main: Democrats and White House Race to Strike Deal for Coronavirus Relief Package
headline.print_headline: Leaders Race to Reach  Deal on Relief Package

byline.original: By Sheryl Gay Stolberg, Jim Tankersley and Alan Rappeport

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump moved on Monday to address the economic effects of the widening coronavirus crisis by announcing that he would work with Congress on tax cuts and other measures after the worst stock market drop in more than a decade.

headline.main: Trump Floats Economic Stimulus in Response to Coronavirus
headline.print_headline: Trump Suggests Economic Stimulus to Bolster an Economy Undergoing a Battering

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court on Wednesday allowed the Trump administration to maintain a program that has forced about 60,000 asylum seekers to wait in Mexico while their requests are heard. An appeals court had blocked the program, saying it was at odds with both federal law and international treaties and was causing “extreme and irreversible harm.”

headline.main: Supreme Court Revives ‘Remain in Mexico’ Policy for Asylum Seekers

byline.original: By Adam Liptak and Zolan Kanno-Youngs

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Four nations that are among the Trump administration’s top diplomatic adversaries were singled out on Wednesday for rampant human rights violations, raising questions of whether the State Department’s annual review of civil liberties protections worldwide was being politicized.

headline.main: Critics Hear Political Tone as Pompeo Calls Out Diplomatic Rivals Over Human Rights
headline.print_headline: Pompeo’s List of Top Human Rights Scofflaws Focuses on Trump Targets
